name: General cargo above 10.000dwt
description: Emission intensity of a general cargo. More than 10000 dwt. The dwt value corresponds to deadweight tonnage, a measure of how much weight a ship can carry. International shipping. New Zealand. Published by the Ministry for the Environment of New Zealand in 2020.

name: General cargo above 10.000dwt and 100teu
description: Emission intensity of a general cargo. Above 10000 dwt and 100 teu. The dwt value here corresponds to deadweight tonnage, a measure of how much weight a ship can carry. Teu refers to twenty-foot equivalent unit. The twenty-foot equivalent unit used here is an inexact unit of cargo capacity, often resorted to for container ships and container ports. International shipping. New Zealand. Published by the Ministry for the Environment of New Zealand in 2020.

name: General cargo average
description: Emission intensity of a general cargo. Average value. International shipping. New Zealand. Published by the Ministry for the Environment of New Zealand in 2020.

name: General cargo below 4.999dwt
description: Emission intensity of a general cargo. Between 0 and 4999 dwt. The dwt value corresponds to deadweight tonnage, a measure of how much weight a ship can carry. International shipping. New Zealand. Published by the Ministry for the Environment of New Zealand in 2020.

name: General cargo below 4.999dwt and above 100teu
description: Emission intensity of a general cargo. Between 0 and 4999 dwt and above 100 teu. The dwt value here corresponds to deadweight tonnage, a measure of how much weight a ship can carry. Teu refers to twenty-foot equivalent unit. The twenty-foot equivalent unit used here is an inexact unit of cargo capacity, often resorted to for container ships and container ports. International shipping. International shipping. New Zealand. Published by the Ministry for the Environment of New Zealand in 2020.

name: General cargo between 5.000 and 9.999dwt
description: Emission intensity of general cargo. Between 5000 and 9999 dwt. The dwt value corresponds to deadweight tonnage, a measure of how much weight a ship can carry. International shipping. New Zealand. Published by the Ministry for the Environment of New Zealand in 2020.

name: General cargo between 5.000 and 9.999dwt and above 100teu
description: Emission intensity of a general cargo. Between 5000 and 9999 dwt and above 100 teu. The dwt value here corresponds to deadweight tonnage, a measure of how much weight a ship can carry. Teu refers to twenty-foot equivalent unit. The twenty-foot equivalent unit used here is an inexact unit of cargo capacity, often resorted to for container ships and container ports. International shipping. New Zealand. Published by the Ministry for the Environment of New Zealand in 2020.

name: Overseas ship container medium
description: Emission intensity of overseas ship, energy demand and emissions updated to data for container ship; global average. Weighted average of all container ships modeled after Lloyds (2009) data. Assumptions: 4% below nominal design speed (37.0 km/h); 80% main engine utilization; cargo utilization 65%.  Value applicable to 2020. Provided by the Öko-Institut. Accessed on the 15th of September 2021.

name: Freight ship goods inland
description: Emission intensity of inland waterway vessel in Germany with diesel engine. Value applicable to 2020.  Provided by the Öko-Institut. Accessed on the 15th of September 2021.

name: Overseas ship oil tanker suez max
description: Emission intensity of overseas vessel, energy demand and emissions data for crude oil tankers and bulk carriers (liquid and dry), Suez Trade, i.e., vessels that can transit the Suez Canal. Oil Bunker-C (2% S). Weighted average of vessels 80,000 - 200,000 dwt (Aframax - Suezmax) modeled after Lloyds (2009) data. Assumptions: 4% below nominal design speed (26.1 km/h); 80% main engine utilization; cargo utilization 50% as mean from Buhaug (2008). These ships cannot pass through the Panama Canal! Value applicable to 2020. Provided by the Öko-Institut. Accessed on the 15th of September 2021.

name: Overseas ship general cargo freighter (panamax)
description: Emission intensity of overseas vessel, energy demand and emissions for bulk carriers (solid) ore, steel, coal, etc.; typical vessel optimized for Panama Canal. Weighted average of ships 60,000 - 80,000 dwt (Panamax) modeled after Lloyds (2009) data. Assumptions: 4% below nominal design speed (25.3 km/h). Value applicable to 2020. Provided by the Öko-Institut. Accessed on the 15th of September 2021.
